Ford GoBike 2019 System Data¶

by Sagar Bilwal¶

Bay Wheels is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California operated by Motivate in a partnership with the Metropolitan Transportation Commission and the Bay Area Air Quality Management District. Bay Wheels is the first regional and large-scale bicycle sharing system deployed in California and on the West Coast of the United States. It was established as Bay Area Bike Share in August 2013. On June 28, 2017, the system officially re-launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company. After Motivate's acquisition by Lyft, the system was subsequently renamed to Bay Wheels in June 2019.

In this project I am exploring Ford GoBike 2019 data downloaded from https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/system-data

Downloading the zip files and saving it¶

In [26]:
def sample_data_zip_download(data_save_path,year,prefix_url,postfix_url,alt_postfix_url):
    try:
        for month in range(1,13):
            if month <10:
                month_str = '0'+str(month)
            else:
                month_str = str(month)
            if year == '2019' and month > 4:
                postfix_url = alt_postfix_url
            system_data_url = prefix_url+ year + month_str + postfix_url
            print (month_str + ' started on ' + system_data_url)
            response = requests.get(system_data_url)
            system_data = ZipFile(BytesIO(response.content))
            #extracting contents of the zipped file and saving it 'data_save_path'
            system_data.extractall(data_save_path)
            print (month_str + ' done')
    except requests.ConnectionError:
        print('Failed to Establish Connection')

#as our data is divided into 12 files according to different months I will concat whole into a single dataframe

for file_name in listdir(data_save_path):
    ford_gobike_csv_list.append(pd.read_csv(data_save_path+'/'+file_name,sep = ','))
ford_gobike_df = pd.concat(ford_gobike_csv_list,ignore_index= True)

Cleaning the dataset¶

Before the visualization it is necessary that I clean the dataset hence following changes will be made¶

i) Convert start and end time to timestamp from string, dividing it into three columns i.e. month, day, hour and converting duration_sec into duration_min as lowest value is 60.¶
ii) Drop rental_access_method¶
iii) Find distance between end and start station using latitude and longitude¶
iv) Dropping all null values rows from the dataset¶
In [24]:
ford_gobike_copy_df = ford_gobike_df.copy()

Define¶

Start and end time are stored as string hence have to be converted to timestamp and the further dividing into three columns each i.e. month, day and hour these three column will help in figuring out when highest users use the bikes.

Code¶

In [25]:
# converting to timestamp

ford_gobike_copy_df.start_time = pd.to_datetime(ford_gobike_copy_df.start_time)
ford_gobike_copy_df.end_time = pd.to_datetime(ford_gobike_copy_df.end_time)

# now handling start and end time as timestamp and dividing it into month, days and hour
# start_time

ford_gobike_copy_df['start_month'] = ford_gobike_copy_df.start_time.dt.strftime('%b')
ford_gobike_copy_df['start_day'] = ford_gobike_copy_df.start_time.dt.strftime('%a')
ford_gobike_copy_df['start_hour'] = ford_gobike_copy_df.start_time.map(lambda x: x.hour)

# end_time

ford_gobike_copy_df['end_month'] = ford_gobike_copy_df.end_time.dt.strftime('%b')
ford_gobike_copy_df['end_day'] = ford_gobike_copy_df.end_time.dt.strftime('%a')
ford_gobike_copy_df['end_hour'] = ford_gobike_copy_df.end_time.map(lambda x: x.hour)

# also convert duration from seconds to minutes as seconds value is very large and minutes will be easy to visualize
ford_gobike_copy_df['duration_min']= ford_gobike_copy_df.duration_sec.map(lambda x: x/60)
In [26]:
# dropping start_time and end_time as we do not require it for visualization
ford_gobike_copy_df.drop(['start_time','end_time','duration_sec'], axis=1, inplace = True)

Define¶

To find distance between start and end station using the latitude and longitude

Code¶

In [34]:
# calculating distance between start and end point in kilometers
ford_gobike_copy_df['distance_miles'] = 3958.756 * 2 * \
np.arcsin(np.sqrt(np.sin((np.radians(ford_gobike_copy_df['end_station_latitude']) - np.radians(ford_gobike_copy_df['start_station_latitude']))/2)**2 + \
                  np.cos(np.radians(ford_gobike_copy_df['start_station_latitude'])) 
                * np.cos(np.radians(ford_gobike_copy_df['end_station_latitude'])) * 
                  np.sin((np.radians(ford_gobike_copy_df['end_station_longitude']) - np.radians(ford_gobike_copy_df['start_station_longitude']))/2)**2))

Preliminary Wrangling¶

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

Initally -> Rows = 2506983; Columns = 15;

After Cleaning -> Rows = 2262979; Columns = 15;

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in the dataset?¶

The main features of interest in my dataset will be as follows -

1) Most used start and end station (total 446 unique stations are available) which will help to figure out where does Ford GoBike recieve maximum users

2) Which time of the day/month Ford GoBike receive maximum users

3) Total Distance travelled and time taken by users

4) Difference between usage by customers and subscribers

Features in the dataset ?¶

Before Cleaning¶

According to me in case of rental_access_method it will not be of much help as almost 95% of the values are not available and also in case of bike_share_for_all_trip about 9.7% of data is not available but the available data will be enough for exploration. Also Start station and end station id will not be of any use for me as we already have station names .Hence I will mainly use 12 features for my investigation.

After Cleaning¶

About 9.7% of rows were dropped to remove null values, few new columns were added which are as follows - 1) start_month, 2) start_day, 3) start_hour, 4) end_month, 5) end_day, 6) end_hour, 7) duration_min, 8) distance_miles and I dropped some of the columns from the dataset after which I have total 15 columns/features to help me with visualizations.
